(chapter
  :book             "Book of CS Curriculum"
  :chapter-number   6
  :title            "06-search-and-sort"
  :source-path      "/Users/alfred/code/curator/BOOK/A-branch-scheme-books/cs-curriculum/06-search-and-sort.slat"
  :size             7335
  :sha256           "c35be27fa886587c"
  :prose
"(chapter
  :n 08
  :title \"Search — how to find something in a lot of things\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You lost your keys. There are three shapes of the search you might
   do. Linear — look at every place, one at a time, until you find
   them. Binary — if you already know your places are sorted (say,
   alphabetized bookshelf and you're looking for The Odyssey), open
   at the middle and eliminate half at each step. Guided — you have
   a hunch (I probably left them at the door); check the hunches
   first, then fall back to systematic. All three show up in
   computing under precise names.\"

  :what-it-is
  \"Search is finding an item (or determining it isn't present) in a
   collection. The efficiency of search is set by two things: how
   the collection is organized, and how much you know about the
   item ahead of time.\"

  :linear-search
  \"Walk the collection one at a time. O(N). Works on unsorted data.
   Bad for large N. Fine when you don't know anything about the
   collection's order.\"

  :binary-search
  \"On a sorted collection: check the middle element; if the target
   is less, recurse on the left half; if greater, the right half;
   if equal, done. O(log N). One of the great small tricks in
   computing. Only works if the collection is sorted.\"

  :graph-searches
  \"For structured collections that aren't linear:
   DFS — go deep first, backtrack; uses a stack.
   BFS — go wide first, level by level; uses a queue.
   Dijkstra — like BFS but respects edge weights; uses a heap.
   A* — Dijkstra plus a heuristic that estimates remaining distance;
   the standard for game AI and route planning.\"

  :indexed-search
  \"For huge collections, you don't search — you index. A hash table
   gives O(1) key lookup. A B-tree index gives O(log N) key lookup
   with efficient range scans. Full-text search engines (Lucene,
   Elasticsearch) precompute inverted indexes: for each word, a
   sorted list of documents containing it. Search then intersects
   the sorted lists for each query term.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; Linear search
   (define (linear-search lst target)
     (cond
       ((null? lst) #f)
       ((equal? (car lst) target) #t)
       (else (linear-search (cdr lst) target))))

   ; Binary search on a vector
   (define (binary-search v target)
     (let loop ((lo 0) (hi (- (vector-length v) 1)))
       (if (> lo hi)
           #f
           (let* ((mid (quotient (+ lo hi) 2))
                  (val (vector-ref v mid)))
             (cond
               ((= val target) mid)
               ((< val target) (loop (+ mid 1) hi))
               (else (loop lo (- mid 1))))))))\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Peirce's abduction is the shape of guided search — a hunch guiding
   the exploration. A* is compiled abduction. Popper would notice
   that binary search leans on a bold conjecture (the collection is
   sorted) that would be catastrophically wrong to hold falsely —
   the invariant must be true or the search is a lie.\")

(chapter
  :n 09
  :title \"Sorting — putting things in order\"
  :book \"book-of-cs-curriculum\"

  :scene
  \"You have a stack of index cards on the desk, thirty of them, and
   you want them in alphabetical order. There are many ways. Pick
   two at a time, swap if wrong, keep going. Or lay them all out and
   find the smallest, put it first, then the smallest of the rest,
   and so on. Or split the pile in half, sort each half somehow,
   then merge the two sorted halves. Each of these is a real
   sorting algorithm.\"

  :what-it-is
  \"Sorting arranges a collection into a defined order. It is one of
   the most-studied problems in computing, because sorting once
   turns many other problems (search, dedup, priority) into fast
   operations.\"

  :o-n-squared-sorts
  \"Bubble sort. Insertion sort. Selection sort. All O(N^2). All simple.
   Insertion sort is genuinely good for small N (say, N < 50) and
   for nearly-sorted data (it is O(N) in the best case). Selection
   sort is easy to remember. Bubble sort is a pedagogical stepping
   stone but rarely used in practice.\"

  :o-n-log-n-sorts
  \"Merge sort. Quick sort. Heap sort. All O(N log N).
   Merge sort — split in half, sort each half, merge. Stable (equal
   elements keep their original order). O(N) extra memory. The go-to
   for linked lists and for external sorting on disk.
   Quick sort — pick a pivot, partition around it, recurse on each
   side. Average O(N log N), worst O(N^2) with a bad pivot choice.
   In-place. The go-to for arrays in most standard libraries.
   Heap sort — build a heap from the array, then repeatedly extract
   the root. O(N log N) worst case, O(1) extra memory.\"

  :specialized-sorts
  \"Radix sort — O(N * k) where k is the number of digits. Not
   comparison-based. Fast for integers and strings.
   Counting sort — O(N + k) where k is the range of values. Only
   works when the value range is small.
   Bucket sort — spread values into buckets, sort within each,
   concatenate.
   Topological sort — for DAGs, produces an ordering respecting
   dependencies. Not a comparison sort in the usual sense; it uses
   the graph structure.\"

  :the-lower-bound
  \"Comparison-based sorting cannot do better than O(N log N). The
   proof is a beautiful counting argument: sorting is choosing among
   N! permutations, and each comparison distinguishes at most 2
   possibilities, so at least log(N!) = O(N log N) comparisons are
   needed. Radix and counting sorts beat this only because they
   are not comparison-based.\"

  :scheme-code
  \"; Merge sort
   (define (merge-sort lst)
     (if (or (null? lst) (null? (cdr lst)))
         lst
         (let-values (((left right) (split-half lst)))
           (merge (merge-sort left) (merge-sort right)))))

   (define (split-half lst)
     (let loop ((slow lst) (fast lst) (acc '()))
       (if (or (null? fast) (null? (cdr fast)))
           (values (reverse acc) slow)
           (loop (cdr slow) (cddr fast) (cons (car slow) acc)))))

   (define (merge a b)
     (cond
       ((null? a) b)
       ((null? b) a)
       ((< (car a) (car b))
        (cons (car a) (merge (cdr a) b)))
       (else
        (cons (car b) (merge a (cdr b))))))

   ; Quick sort (Scheme-idiomatic; not in-place)
   (define (quick-sort lst)
     (if (or (null? lst) (null? (cdr lst)))
         lst
         (let ((pivot (car lst)) (rest (cdr lst)))
           (append
             (quick-sort (filter (lambda (x) (< x pivot)) rest))
             (list pivot)
             (quick-sort (filter (lambda (x) (>= x pivot)) rest))))))\"

  :where-in-the-world
  \"Every language's standard library has a sort. Most use Timsort
   (Python, Java) or introsort (C++). Databases sort during query
   execution (ORDER BY, GROUP BY, joins). Compilers sort during
   register allocation. Search engines sort by relevance. Almost
   everything sorts something.\"

  :philosophy-lens
  \"Aristotle would appreciate the arc — collection unsorted (a
   beginning), some algorithm applies (a middle), collection sorted
   (an end aimed at). The final cause is the arrangement. Wittgenstein-
   late would note that 'order' means what a community of code
   agrees it means — sorted-by-name-ascending, sorted-by-relevance,
   sorted-by-time-added. Sorting is a language-game with many
   variants.\")
")
